{"title_page": "SB.TV", "text_new": "{{puffery}}\n{{short description|British music outlet}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = SB.TV\n| logo             = SB.TV_logo.png\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Privately held company|Privately held]]\n| traded_as        = \n| genre            = [[Grime (music)|Grime]], [[British hip hop]], [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 2 November 2006<br><small>(active from 25 August 2010 onwards)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://companycheck.co.uk/company/07356398|title=SBTV Global Ltd|last=|first=|date=10 November 2011|publisher=Company Check|accessdate=10 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305193556/http://companycheck.co.uk/company/07356398|archive-date=5 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| defunct          = \n| location         = 145-157 [[St John Street, London|St John Street]],<br />[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]]\n| industry         = [[Entertainment industry|Entertainment]], [[music industry|music]]\n| products         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| founders          = Jamal Edwards, Liam Tootill, James Hanna, Georgia LA, Lily Mercer, Rick Tank\n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = [http://www.sbtv.co.uk/ sbtv.co.uk]\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n'''SB.TV Global Ltd''', also known as '''SB.TV''' or '''SmokeyBarz''', is a multi-faceted British company founded by Jamal Edwards and a small team of young people who work on web-based content, generally with a new music angle. The media platform has its origins and roots in [[urban music]]. Most of the content can be seen on its own [[YouTube]] channel, which was created on 2 November 2006, or on the official SB.TV website and includes unprofessional footage, or \"street-shot\" [[freestyle raps]] and [[music videos]]. However, even though its earlier uploaded videos contained entirely amateur footage, the channel's latest uploads contain professional recordings and a less is more approach is taken. SB.TV have diversified into events and have curated stages at Bestival, Wireless, Outlook and other internationally renowned festivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisfestivalfeeling.com/news/sbtv-host-stage-yahoo-wireless|title=SB.TV to Host Stage at Yahoo! Wireless|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529154022/http://www.thisfestivalfeeling.com/news/sbtv-host-stage-yahoo-wireless|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> SB.TV were also invited to film interviews with a host of leading politicians at 10 Downing Street, including the Prime Minister David Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/10/sb-tv-jamal-edwards-interviews-david-cameron-at-downing-st-spirit-of-london-awards-2011/|title=SB.TV - Jamal Edwards interviews David Cameron at Downing St - Spirit of London Awards 2011 - SBTV|author=SBTV|work=SBTV|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529162247/http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/10/sb-tv-jamal-edwards-interviews-david-cameron-at-downing-st-spirit-of-london-awards-2011/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Edwards has also built a relationship with the Royal Family and first interviewed Prince Charles in 2013.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/the-jamal-edwards-effect-generation-success--the-media-savvy-stars-taking-over-the-world-wide-web-8844505.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Ian | last=Burrell | title=The Jamal Edwards effect: Generation success - the media savvy stars taking over the world (wide web) | date=27 September 2013 | access-date=11 September 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925015329/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/the-jamal-edwards-effect-generation-success--the-media-savvy-stars-taking-over-the-world-wide-web-8844505.html | archive-date=25 September 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe reasonable popularity of the channel among London's underground scene has led to features in ''[[RWD Magazine|RWD]]'', ''[[The Observer]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]'', the ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times Style]]'' magazine, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' and ''[[GQ]]'' while founder Jamal Edwards has been on the front cover of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', ''[[Intelligent Life (magazine)|Intelligent Life]]'' and the Emirates In-flight magazine. SB.TV also has assistant production credits from when Edwards was working as a junior runner for the [[BBC]], and [[Tiger Aspect Productions]] as well as joining the young persons panel at ''The Guardian''{{'}}s new technology conference activate summit alongside [[Martha Lane Fox]] and others.<ref>Spicer, Kate, ''Sunday Times Style'': \"He is typical of many entrepreneurial satellite characters who are turning grime into not just a sound, but a movement.. Ed Balls\u2019s Department for Children, Schools and Families wants precisely Edwards\u2019 (ME) breed of ingenuity to infect some of the hardest to reach kids in the country\".</ref> Today, the YouTube channel has gained many millions of views and thousands of subscribers, as well as [[Facebook]] fans and [[Twitter]] followers.<ref>Ajilore, Joseph, [http://yourhiddenpotential.co.uk/2011/05/27/jamal-edwards-sbtv/ \"The rise and rise of a new media mogul \u2013 Jamal Edwards of SBTV\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917180618/http://yourhiddenpotential.co.uk/2011/05/27/jamal-edwards-sbtv/ |date=2011-09-17 }}, ''Your Hidden Potential'' (YHP), 27 May 2011: \"SB.TV has since reached over 70<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS NUMBER, QUOTES ARE NOT SUBJECT TO CHANGE. --> million viewers on YouTube becoming one of the most subscribed channels on YouTube attracting people from all over the world.\"</ref> SB.TV has been credited with 'discovering' [[Ed Sheeran]] whose music was aired exclusively on the channel in February 2010 - a full year before he achieved worldwide fame. SB.TV has been said to attract higher audiences of young people than ITV.<ref>{{cite web|title = Home-made TV from London to change everything|url = http://www.flashesandflames.com/2012/09/tv-revolution-from-west-london-that-threatens-to-change-everything/|website = Flashes & Flames|accessdate = 2015-12-04|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151115003344/http://www.flashesandflames.com/2012/09/tv-revolution-from-west-london-that-threatens-to-change-everything/|archive-date = 2015-11-15|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSB.TV YouTube channel was created in 2006, when a teenage '''Jamal Edwards''' MBE<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30635123 \"Music boss gets New Year Honours\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235010/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30635123 |date=2019-02-26 }}. BBC News, (2014). Accessed 31 December 2014.</ref><!--Born 24 August 1990--> (son of singer and TV presenter [[Brenda Edwards]]) began filming rap freestyles with a [[handycam]], which he would then upload to his YouTube account. For the first three years Edwards acted alone to provide amateur footage of many British [[Grime (music)|grime]]<ref>Fiddy, Chantelle (June 2010), [http://www.exacteditions.com/exact/browse/396/434/7085/3/30 \"SB.TV\u2019s Jamal is Grime\u2019s Simon Cowell\"], ''Dazed & Confused'', p. 28.</ref> artists, such as [[Dizzee Rascal]], [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]], [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]] and [[Tinchy Stryder]], with the first SB.TV video being uploaded in February 2007.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/3270910/jamal-edwards-story/ | work=Time | title=Jamal Edwards got his first video camera when was 15 | date=12 September 2014 | access-date=29 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529180846/http://time.com/3270910/jamal-edwards-story/ | archive-date=29 May 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> A Channel 4 documentary series, Bedroom to Boardroom that follows SB.TV was filmed in Edwards first office, [[Camden Collective]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = What's next for London? The High Life Future of London forum|url = http://highlife.ba.com/articles/whats-next-for-london-the-high-life-future-of-london-forum/|website = British Airways High Life|accessdate = 2015-10-30|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151120193141/http://highlife.ba.com/articles/whats-next-for-london-the-high-life-future-of-london-forum/|archive-date = 2015-11-20|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Inside SBTV: From Bedroom to Boardroom|url = http://www.channel4.com/programmes/inside-sbtv-from-bedroom-to-boardroom|website = Channel 4|accessdate = 2015-10-30|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151120194340/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/inside-sbtv-from-bedroom-to-boardroom|archive-date = 2015-11-20|url-status = live}}</ref> As the channel began to attract more attention, it also began offering lifestyle interviews and event coverage, and a production team of ten people was established as a result.\n\nRecently, the company has cited its aim to become a more \"diverse youth lifestyle broadcaster\", incorporating more genres of music.<ref>\"It is the drive to succeed at the very highest level that motivates SB.TV\", ''[[RWD magazine|RWD]]''.</ref> This has been seen in the inclusion of [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] artists such as [[Ed Sheeran]] and other [[Pop music|popular]] artists such as [[Jessie J]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[The Wanted]] and [[Pixie Lott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outside-org.co.uk/2011/11/jamal-edwards-biography/|title=Having expanded his repertoire \u2013 Jessie J, Nicki Minaj, The Wanted and Pixie Lott among the many celebrities who\u2019ve now exclusively spoken to or performed for Jamal \u2013 SB.TV has become a set fixture on the major label-marketing plan and beyond.|last1=Goodman|first1=Chris|last2=Okoye|first2=Felicia|date=1 November 2011|publisher=Outside Organisation|accessdate=19 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402224649/http://outside-org.co.uk/2011/11/jamal-edwards-biography/|archive-date=2 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In February 2011, SB.TV launched their own music label ''Just Jam'' (an imprint of [[RCA Records|Sony RCA]]) and recently announced their first signing as east London [[MC]], Maxsta.<ref>[http://www.urbandevelopment.co.uk/blog-categories/features-reviews/features/profiles/brand-profile-sbtv_1844 SB.TV brand profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518132541/http://urbandevelopment.co.uk/blog-categories/features-reviews/features/profiles/brand-profile-sbtv_1844 |date=2011-05-18 }} &mdash; Urban Development.</ref> In March 2011 it had been suggested that the company were expected to go into business with restaurant chain [[Nando's]].<ref>[http://madnews.wordpress.com/2011/03/31/uk-news-sb-tv-and-nandos-doing-business-together/ \"UK News: SB.TV and Nandos Chicken Set To Do Business Together?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817051638/http://madnews.wordpress.com/2011/03/31/uk-news-sb-tv-and-nandos-doing-business-together/ |date=2011-08-17 }} Mad News, 31 March 2011.</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, Edwards was featured in a [[Google Chrome]] advertisement by London advertising agency [[BBH (Bartle, Bogle & Hegarty) Advertising Agency|BBH]], which tracked the emergence of SB.TV as one of among many of the UK's rising youth broadcasters.<ref>[http://wearesme.co.uk/2011/08/21/news-video-sbtv-founder-jamal-edwards-stars-in-new-google-chrome-advert/ \"SBTV Founder Jamal Edwards Stars In New Google Chrome Advert\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120718065848/http://wearesme.co.uk/2011/08/21/news-video-sbtv-founder-jamal-edwards-stars-in-new-google-chrome-advert/ |date=2012-07-18 }} &mdash; We Are S.M.E.</ref> The SB.TV website subsequently crashed as close to a million people searched \"Jamal Edwards.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23989269-the-acton-kid-and-his-media-empire.do|title=Jamal Edwards ... the Acton kid and his media empire|last=Rai|first=Rajvir|date=22 September 2011|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=15 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024191904/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23989269-the-acton-kid-and-his-media-empire.do|archive-date=24 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The advert was revealed to be the second most watched video advertisement on [[YouTube]] in the UK in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://plus.google.com/103583604759580854844/posts/L2XkcsbgzzD|title=The UK\u2019s top ten most popular YouTube video ads in 2011|last=|first=|date=6 December 2011|publisher=[[Google]] UK|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2012, SB.TV released a video with grime collective [[Boy Better Know]], to celebrate reaching 100 million views across all videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ei09chGK2EM|title=Boy Better Know 100M YouTube views - [CYPHER]: SBTV|access-date=2014-10-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628073516/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ei09chGK2EM|archive-date=2014-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Susana Giner, director of the Youth Media Agency told The Independent newspaper there was a marketing term been adopted in Edwards namesake; 'The Jamal Edwards effect', a newly adopted ideology that anything\u2019s possible in the digital age.\n<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn 2013 Edwards became the first YouTuber to release an e-book and interactive game, \u2018Self Belief: The Vision', which subsequently became a no.1 best seller with demand leading to an unintended print version via Virgin Books.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.virgin.com/news/jamal-edwards-presents-self-belief-vision |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529174443/http://www.virgin.com/news/jamal-edwards-presents-self-belief-vision |archive-date=2015-05-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Further demonstrating his skills set, Edwards worked with ''[[Burberry]]'' as part of Creative Lives,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://events.holmesreport.com/in2-london-2015/speaker-jamal-edwards-627.aspx|title=In2 Innovation Summit|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529200448/http://events.holmesreport.com/in2-london-2015/speaker-jamal-edwards-627.aspx|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> fronted a ''[[Puma AG|Puma]]'' campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketingweek.com/2012/03/02/puma-signs-jamal-edwards-as-brand-ambassador/|title=Puma signs Jamal Edwards as brand ambassador|work=Marketing Week|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529174254/http://www.marketingweek.com/2012/03/02/puma-signs-jamal-edwards-as-brand-ambassador/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> presented at the ''[[BAFTA]]'' Children\u2019s Awards,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/children/awards/british-academy-childrens-awards-ceremony-in-2014|title=British Academy Children\u2019s Awards Ceremony in 2014|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529200127/http://www.bafta.org/children/awards/british-academy-childrens-awards-ceremony-in-2014|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> and delivered talks for ''[[Cannes Lions]]'',<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MhxjRz6N9iw|title=Jamal Edwards (SB.TV) at Cannes Lions 2014|date=17 June 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> TedXHollywood <ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2h_rCXviiMQ|title=The Future of Democracy: Jamal Edwards at TEDxHousesofParliament|date=27 June 2013|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=29 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116073950/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2h_rCXviiMQ|archive-date=16 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and TedXHousesOfParliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tedxhousesofparliament.com/2013/speakers/jamal-edwards|title=Jamal Edwards \u2039 Speakers \u2039 2013 \u2039 TEDxHousesOfParliament|work=TEDx Houses of Parliament|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529201429/http://www.tedxhousesofparliament.com/2013/speakers/jamal-edwards|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> In a nod to his grandparents, he received an St Vincent Business Award in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwnsvg.com/2013/12/05/vincentian-entrepreneurs-awarded-in-the-uk/|title=Vincentian entrepreneurs awarded in the UK|work=iWitness News|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529203009/http://www.iwnsvg.com/2013/12/05/vincentian-entrepreneurs-awarded-in-the-uk/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEdwards was honoured when he became one of the Queen\u2019s Young Leaders,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jubileetribute.org/program/youth-leadership/the-queens-young-leaders/|title=The Queen's Young Leaders - The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|author=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|work=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529195853/http://jubileetribute.org/program/youth-leadership/the-queens-young-leaders/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> after being called upon to run the first ever social media hub at ''[[Buckingham Palace]]''. Achievements like this saw Jamal placed at no. 2 in The Guardian\u2019s top 30 young people in digital media 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/16/top-30-young-people-digital-media-nos-30-11|title=The top 30 young people in digital media: Nos 30-11|author=Matt Andrews|work=the Guardian|access-date=2016-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107084917/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/16/top-30-young-people-digital-media-nos-30-11|archive-date=2016-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Edwards was invited to collaborate with American Freshman on a headware range for ''[[Topman]]''. The snapbacks and bucket hats went on sale in the summer to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topman.com/en/tmuk/category/clothing-140502/jamal-edwards-x-american-freshman-3465643|title=Clothing|work=topman.com|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529163601/http://www.topman.com/en/tmuk/category/clothing-140502/jamal-edwards-x-american-freshman-3465643|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nImpressed by one aspiring entrepreneur, Joe Carnell, in 2014 they went into business together and they\u2019re now the proud co-founders of UGOT, a yogurt, juice and health bar chain. Already winning awards in Yorkshire, there\u2019s a branch open in Newcastle with plans afoot for Manchester and Leeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sophieahcornish.blogspot.co.uk/2014/04/15-minutes-with-ugot-cofounder-joe.html|title=Sophie's Choice: 15 MINUTES WITH UGOT COFOUNDER: JOE CARNELL|author=What Sophie Did|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529195903/http://sophieahcornish.blogspot.co.uk/2014/04/15-minutes-with-ugot-cofounder-joe.html|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Edwards was appointed a MBE for his services to music.<ref name=BBC /><ref>Rykesha Hudson, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/young-entrepreneur-jamal-edwards-honoured-queen \"Young Entrepreneur Jamal Edwards Honoured By Queen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101161525/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/young-entrepreneur-jamal-edwards-honoured-queen |date=2015-01-01 }}, ''The Voice'', 30 December 2014. Accessed 1 January 2015.</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, SBTV announced the launch of SBTV News, an online news service, in partnership with the Press Association, chaired by former EMAP, Hearst, Axel Springer and Future CEO Colin Morrison<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/jan/20/youtube-sbtv-pa-vice-news|title=YouTube video channel SBTV links with PA for youth news service|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2016-01-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319014911/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/jan/20/youtube-sbtv-pa-vice-news|archive-date=2017-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nSBTV is built on three core services: broadcasting, production and editorial services.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SB.TV logo.PNG|thumb|right|The old logo (2010-16)]] -->\n\n===Broadcasting===\nSBTV  continue to broadcast video whether for music, freestyle, acoustic, interviews or any other categories within youth culture. All of the company's content is displayed on their YouTube channel. This content is mainly produced by SBTV but they do allow submissions as well. The company also uses social networking extensively to interact with viewers through which new blog and news articles are published.\n\n===Production===\nJust like broadcasting, SBTV has always produced its own content and have developed new techniques over time. Most of the content is shot in \"fast and agile situations\" to deliver an enticing perspective for the viewer. Among the videos that are shot, produced and directed by SBTV are music videos, documentaries and SBTV event material.\n\n===Editorial===\nThe majority of employees at SBTV have experience in various printed urban publications and therefore know how to present material to a younger audience. This includes providing the latest news on music releases, films, music videos and artists.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Link Up TV]]\n* [[Mixtape Madness]]\n* [[GRM Daily]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sbtv.co.uk/ sbtv.co.uk]\n*{{youtube|user=smokeybarz}}\n\n[[Category:British music industry]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:British music websites]]\n[[Category:Hip hop websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{puffery}}\n{{short description|British music outlet}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = SB.TV\n| logo             = SB.TV_logo.png\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Privately held company|Privately held]]\n| traded_as        = \n| genre            = [[Grime (music)|Grime]], [[British hip hop]], [[acoustic music|acoustic]]\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 2 November 2006<br><small>(active from 25 August 2010 onwards)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://companycheck.co.uk/company/07356398|title=SBTV Global Ltd|last=|first=|date=10 November 2011|publisher=Company Check|accessdate=10 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305193556/http://companycheck.co.uk/company/07356398|archive-date=5 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| defunct          = \n| location         = 145-157 [[St John Street, London|St John Street]],<br />[[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]]\n| industry         = [[Entertainment industry|Entertainment]], [[music industry|music]]\n| products         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| founders          = Jamal Edwards, Liam Tootill, James Hanna, Georgia LA, Lily Mercer, Rick Tank\n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = [http://www.sbtv.co.uk/ sbtv.co.uk]\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n'''SB.TV Global Ltd''', also known as '''SB.TV''' or '''SmokeyBarz''', is a multi-faceted British company founded by Jamal Edwards and a small team of young people who work on web-based content, generally with a new music angle. The media platform has its origins and roots in [[urban music]]. Most of the content can be seen on its own [[YouTube]] channel, which was created on 2 November 2006, or on the official SB.TV website and includes unprofessional footage, or \"street-shot\" [[freestyle raps]] and [[music videos]]. However, even though its earlier uploaded videos contained entirely amateur footage, the channel's latest uploads contain professional recordings and a less is more approach is taken. SB.TV have diversified into events and have curated stages at Bestival, Wireless, Outlook and other internationally renowned festivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisfestivalfeeling.com/news/sbtv-host-stage-yahoo-wireless|title=SB.TV to Host Stage at Yahoo! Wireless|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529154022/http://www.thisfestivalfeeling.com/news/sbtv-host-stage-yahoo-wireless|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> SB.TV were also invited to film interviews with a host of leading politicians at 10 Downing Street, including the Prime Minister David Cameron.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/10/sb-tv-jamal-edwards-interviews-david-cameron-at-downing-st-spirit-of-london-awards-2011/|title=SB.TV - Jamal Edwards interviews David Cameron at Downing St - Spirit of London Awards 2011 - SBTV|author=SBTV|work=SBTV|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529162247/http://sbtv.co.uk/2011/10/sb-tv-jamal-edwards-interviews-david-cameron-at-downing-st-spirit-of-london-awards-2011/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Edwards has also built a relationship with the Royal Family and first interviewed Prince Charles in 2013.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/the-jamal-edwards-effect-generation-success--the-media-savvy-stars-taking-over-the-world-wide-web-8844505.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Ian | last=Burrell | title=The Jamal Edwards effect: Generation success - the media savvy stars taking over the world (wide web) | date=27 September 2013 | access-date=11 September 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925015329/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/the-jamal-edwards-effect-generation-success--the-media-savvy-stars-taking-over-the-world-wide-web-8844505.html | archive-date=25 September 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe reasonable popularity of the channel among London's underground scene has led to features in ''[[RWD Magazine|RWD]]'', ''[[The Observer]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]'', the ''[[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times Style]]'' magazine, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' and ''[[GQ]]'' while founder Jamal Edwards has been on the front cover of ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'', ''[[Intelligent Life (magazine)|Intelligent Life]]'' and the Emirates In-flight magazine. SB.TV also has assistant production credits from when Edwards was working as a junior runner for the [[BBC]], and [[Tiger Aspect Productions]] as well as joining the young persons panel at ''The Guardian''{{'}}s new technology conference activate summit alongside [[Martha Lane Fox]] and others.<ref>Spicer, Kate, ''Sunday Times Style'': \"He is typical of many entrepreneurial satellite characters who are turning grime into not just a sound, but a movement.. Ed Balls\u2019s Department for Children, Schools and Families wants precisely Edwards\u2019 (ME) breed of ingenuity to infect some of the hardest to reach kids in the country\".</ref> Today, the YouTube channel has gained many millions of views and thousands of subscribers, as well as [[Facebook]] fans and [[Twitter]] followers.<ref>Ajilore, Joseph, [http://yourhiddenpotential.co.uk/2011/05/27/jamal-edwards-sbtv/ \"The rise and rise of a new media mogul \u2013 Jamal Edwards of SBTV\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917180618/http://yourhiddenpotential.co.uk/2011/05/27/jamal-edwards-sbtv/ |date=2011-09-17 }}, ''Your Hidden Potential'' (YHP), 27 May 2011: \"SB.TV has since reached over 70<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS NUMBER, QUOTES ARE NOT SUBJECT TO CHANGE. --> million viewers on YouTube becoming one of the most subscribed channels on YouTube attracting people from all over the world.\"</ref> SB.TV has been credited with 'discovering' [[Ed Sheeran]] whose music was aired exclusively on the channel in February 2010 - a full year before he achieved worldwide fame. SB.TV has been said to attract higher audiences of young people than ITV.<ref>{{cite web|title = Home-made TV from London to change everything|url = http://www.flashesandflames.com/2012/09/tv-revolution-from-west-london-that-threatens-to-change-everything/|website = Flashes & Flames|accessdate = 2015-12-04|language = en-US|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151115003344/http://www.flashesandflames.com/2012/09/tv-revolution-from-west-london-that-threatens-to-change-everything/|archive-date = 2015-11-15|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSB.TV YouTube channel was created in 2006, when a teenage '''Jamal Edwards''' MBE<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30635123 \"Music boss gets New Year Honours\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226235010/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30635123 |date=2019-02-26 }}. BBC News, (2014). Accessed 31 December 2014.</ref><!--Born 24 August 1990--> (son of singer and TV presenter [[Brenda Edwards]]) began filming rap freestyles with a [[handycam]], which he would then upload to his YouTube account. For the first three years Edwards acted alone to provide amateur footage of many British [[Grime (music)|grime]]<ref>Fiddy, Chantelle (June 2010), [http://www.exacteditions.com/exact/browse/396/434/7085/3/30 \"SB.TV\u2019s Jamal is Grime\u2019s Simon Cowell\"], ''Dazed & Confused'', p. 28.</ref> artists, such as [[Dizzee Rascal]], [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]], [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]] and [[Tinchy Stryder]], with the first SB.TV video being uploaded in February 2007.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://time.com/3270910/jamal-edwards-story/ | work=Time | title=Jamal Edwards got his first video camera when was 15 | date=12 September 2014 | access-date=29 May 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529180846/http://time.com/3270910/jamal-edwards-story/ | archive-date=29 May 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref> A Channel 4 documentary series, Bedroom to Boardroom that follows SB.TV was filmed in Edwards first office, [[Camden Collective]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = What's next for London? The High Life Future of London forum|url = http://highlife.ba.com/articles/whats-next-for-london-the-high-life-future-of-london-forum/|website = British Airways High Life|accessdate = 2015-10-30|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151120193141/http://highlife.ba.com/articles/whats-next-for-london-the-high-life-future-of-london-forum/|archive-date = 2015-11-20|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Inside SBTV: From Bedroom to Boardroom|url = http://www.channel4.com/programmes/inside-sbtv-from-bedroom-to-boardroom|website = Channel 4|accessdate = 2015-10-30|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151120194340/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/inside-sbtv-from-bedroom-to-boardroom|archive-date = 2015-11-20|url-status = live}}</ref> As the channel began to attract more attention, it also began offering lifestyle interviews and event coverage, and a production team of ten people was established as a result.\n\nRecently, the company has cited its aim to become a more \"diverse youth lifestyle broadcaster\", incorporating more genres of music.<ref>\"It is the drive to succeed at the very highest level that motivates SB.TV\", ''[[RWD magazine|RWD]]''.</ref> This has been seen in the inclusion of [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] artists such as [[Ed Sheeran]] and other [[Pop music|popular]] artists such as [[Jessie J]], [[Nicki Minaj]], [[The Wanted]] and [[Pixie Lott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outside-org.co.uk/2011/11/jamal-edwards-biography/|title=Having expanded his repertoire \u2013 Jessie J, Nicki Minaj, The Wanted and Pixie Lott among the many celebrities who\u2019ve now exclusively spoken to or performed for Jamal \u2013 SB.TV has become a set fixture on the major label-marketing plan and beyond.|last1=Goodman|first1=Chris|last2=Okoye|first2=Felicia|date=1 November 2011|publisher=Outside Organisation|accessdate=19 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402224649/http://outside-org.co.uk/2011/11/jamal-edwards-biography/|archive-date=2 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In February 2011, SB.TV launched their own music label ''Just Jam'' (an imprint of [[RCA Records|Sony RCA]]) and recently announced their first signing as east London [[MC]], Maxsta.<ref>[http://www.urbandevelopment.co.uk/blog-categories/features-reviews/features/profiles/brand-profile-sbtv_1844 SB.TV brand profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518132541/http://urbandevelopment.co.uk/blog-categories/features-reviews/features/profiles/brand-profile-sbtv_1844 |date=2011-05-18 }} &mdash; Urban Development.</ref> In March 2011 it had been suggested that the company were expected to go into business with restaurant chain [[Nando's]].<ref>[http://madnews.wordpress.com/2011/03/31/uk-news-sb-tv-and-nandos-doing-business-together/ \"UK News: SB.TV and Nandos Chicken Set To Do Business Together?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817051638/http://madnews.wordpress.com/2011/03/31/uk-news-sb-tv-and-nandos-doing-business-together/ |date=2011-08-17 }} Mad News, 31 March 2011.</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, Edwards was featured in a [[Google Chrome]] advertisement by London advertising agency [[BBH (Bartle, Bogle & Hegarty) Advertising Agency|BBH]], which tracked the emergence of SB.TV as one of among many of the UK's rising youth broadcasters.<ref>[http://wearesme.co.uk/2011/08/21/news-video-sbtv-founder-jamal-edwards-stars-in-new-google-chrome-advert/ \"SBTV Founder Jamal Edwards Stars In New Google Chrome Advert\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120718065848/http://wearesme.co.uk/2011/08/21/news-video-sbtv-founder-jamal-edwards-stars-in-new-google-chrome-advert/ |date=2012-07-18 }} &mdash; We Are S.M.E.</ref> The SB.TV website subsequently crashed as close to a million people searched \"Jamal Edwards.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23989269-the-acton-kid-and-his-media-empire.do|title=Jamal Edwards ... the Acton kid and his media empire|last=Rai|first=Rajvir|date=22 September 2011|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=15 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111024191904/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/lifestyle/article-23989269-the-acton-kid-and-his-media-empire.do|archive-date=24 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The advert was revealed to be the second most watched video advertisement on [[YouTube]] in the UK in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://plus.google.com/103583604759580854844/posts/L2XkcsbgzzD|title=The UK\u2019s top ten most popular YouTube video ads in 2011|last=|first=|date=6 December 2011|publisher=[[Google]] UK|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2012, SB.TV released a video with grime collective [[Boy Better Know]], to celebrate reaching 100 million views across all videos.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ei09chGK2EM|title=Boy Better Know 100M YouTube views - [CYPHER]: SBTV|access-date=2014-10-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628073516/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ei09chGK2EM|archive-date=2014-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Susana Giner, director of the Youth Media Agency told The Independent newspaper there was a marketing term been adopted in Edwards namesake; 'The Jamal Edwards effect', a newly adopted ideology that anything\u2019s possible in the digital age.\n<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn 2013 Edwards became the first YouTuber to release an e-book and interactive game, \u2018Self Belief: The Vision', which subsequently became a no.1 best seller with demand leading to an unintended print version via Virgin Books.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.virgin.com/news/jamal-edwards-presents-self-belief-vision |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529174443/http://www.virgin.com/news/jamal-edwards-presents-self-belief-vision |archive-date=2015-05-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Further demonstrating his skills set, Edwards worked with ''[[Burberry]]'' as part of Creative Lives,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://events.holmesreport.com/in2-london-2015/speaker-jamal-edwards-627.aspx|title=In2 Innovation Summit|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529200448/http://events.holmesreport.com/in2-london-2015/speaker-jamal-edwards-627.aspx|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> fronted a ''[[Puma AG|Puma]]'' campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketingweek.com/2012/03/02/puma-signs-jamal-edwards-as-brand-ambassador/|title=Puma signs Jamal Edwards as brand ambassador|work=Marketing Week|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529174254/http://www.marketingweek.com/2012/03/02/puma-signs-jamal-edwards-as-brand-ambassador/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> presented at the ''[[BAFTA]]'' Children\u2019s Awards,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/children/awards/british-academy-childrens-awards-ceremony-in-2014|title=British Academy Children\u2019s Awards Ceremony in 2014|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529200127/http://www.bafta.org/children/awards/british-academy-childrens-awards-ceremony-in-2014|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> and delivered talks for ''[[Cannes Lions]]'',<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MhxjRz6N9iw|title=Jamal Edwards (SB.TV) at Cannes Lions 2014|date=17 June 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> TedXHollywood <ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2h_rCXviiMQ|title=The Future of Democracy: Jamal Edwards at TEDxHousesofParliament|date=27 June 2013|publisher=|via=YouTube|access-date=29 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116073950/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2h_rCXviiMQ|archive-date=16 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and TedXHousesOfParliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tedxhousesofparliament.com/2013/speakers/jamal-edwards|title=Jamal Edwards \u2039 Speakers \u2039 2013 \u2039 TEDxHousesOfParliament|work=TEDx Houses of Parliament|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529201429/http://www.tedxhousesofparliament.com/2013/speakers/jamal-edwards|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> In a nod to his grandparents, he received an St Vincent Business Award in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwnsvg.com/2013/12/05/vincentian-entrepreneurs-awarded-in-the-uk/|title=Vincentian entrepreneurs awarded in the UK|work=iWitness News|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529203009/http://www.iwnsvg.com/2013/12/05/vincentian-entrepreneurs-awarded-in-the-uk/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEdwards was honoured when he became one of the Queen\u2019s Young Leaders,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jubileetribute.org/program/youth-leadership/the-queens-young-leaders/|title=The Queen's Young Leaders - The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|author=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|work=The Queen Elizabeth Diamond Jubilee Trust|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529195853/http://jubileetribute.org/program/youth-leadership/the-queens-young-leaders/|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> after being called upon to run the first ever social media hub at ''[[Buckingham Palace]]''. Achievements like this saw Jamal placed at no. 2 in The Guardian\u2019s top 30 young people in digital media 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/16/top-30-young-people-digital-media-nos-30-11|title=The top 30 young people in digital media: Nos 30-11|author=Matt Andrews|work=the Guardian|access-date=2016-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107084917/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/16/top-30-young-people-digital-media-nos-30-11|archive-date=2016-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Edwards was invited to collaborate with American Freshman on a headware range for ''[[Topman]]''. The snapbacks and bucket hats went on sale in the summer to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topman.com/en/tmuk/category/clothing-140502/jamal-edwards-x-american-freshman-3465643|title=Clothing|work=topman.com|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529163601/http://www.topman.com/en/tmuk/category/clothing-140502/jamal-edwards-x-american-freshman-3465643|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nImpressed by one aspiring entrepreneur, Joe Carnell, in 2014 they went into business together and they\u2019re now the proud co-founders of UGOT, a yogurt, juice and health bar chain. Already winning awards in Yorkshire, there\u2019s a branch open in Newcastle with plans afoot for Manchester and Leeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sophieahcornish.blogspot.co.uk/2014/04/15-minutes-with-ugot-cofounder-joe.html|title=Sophie's Choice: 15 MINUTES WITH UGOT COFOUNDER: JOE CARNELL|author=What Sophie Did|publisher=|access-date=2015-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529195903/http://sophieahcornish.blogspot.co.uk/2014/04/15-minutes-with-ugot-cofounder-joe.html|archive-date=2015-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Edwards was appointed a MBE for his services to music.<ref name=BBC /><ref>Rykesha Hudson, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/young-entrepreneur-jamal-edwards-honoured-queen \"Young Entrepreneur Jamal Edwards Honoured By Queen\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101161525/http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/young-entrepreneur-jamal-edwards-honoured-queen |date=2015-01-01 }}, ''The Voice'', 30 December 2014. Accessed 1 January 2015.</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, SBTV announced the launch of SBTV News, an online news service, in partnership with the Press Association, chaired by former EMAP, Hearst, Axel Springer and Future CEO Colin Morrison<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/jan/20/youtube-sbtv-pa-vice-news|title=YouTube video channel SBTV links with PA for youth news service|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=2016-01-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-04-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319014911/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/jan/20/youtube-sbtv-pa-vice-news|archive-date=2017-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nSBTV is built on three core services: broadcasting, production and editorial services.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:SB.TV logo.PNG|thumb|right|The old logo (2010-16)]] -->\n\n===Broadcasting===\nSBTV  continue to broadcast video whether for music, freestyle, acoustic, interviews or any other categories within youth culture. All of the company's content is displayed on their YouTube channel. This content is mainly produced by SBTV but they do allow submissions as well. The company also uses social networking extensively to interact with viewers through which new blog and news articles are published.\n\n===Production===\nJust like broadcasting, SBTV has always produced its own content and have developed new techniques over time. Most of the content is shot in \"fast and agile situations\" to deliver an enticing perspective for the viewer. Among the videos that are shot, produced and directed by SBTV are music videos, documentaries and SBTV event material.\n\n===Editorial===\nThe majority of employees at SBTV have experience in various printed urban publications and therefore know how to present material to a younger audience. This includes providing the latest news on music releases, films, music videos and artists.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sbtv.co.uk/ sbtv.co.uk]\n*{{youtube|user=smokeybarz}}\n\n[[Category:British music industry]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:British music websites]]\n[[Category:Hip hop websites]]\n", "name_user": "Madbrad200", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEditorial:see also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SB.TV"}
{"title_page": "Rod (unit)", "text_new": "{{Infobox unit\n| name     = rod\n| standard = [[imperial units|imperial]]/[[US customary units|US]]&nbsp;units\n| quantity = [[length]]\n| units1   = imperial/US&nbsp;units\n| inunits1 = {{frac|16|1|2}}&nbsp;[[Foot (unit)#United States survey foot|survey ft]]\n| units2   = [[metric system|metric]] ([[SI]]) units\n| inunits2 = {{convert|5.5|yd|m|4|lk=on|disp=out}}\n}}\n\nThe '''rod''' or '''perch''' or '''pole''' (sometimes also '''lug''') is a [[surveying|surveyor's]] tool<ref name=\"Connections\"/> and unit of [[length]] of various historical definitions, often between 3 and 8 [[metre]]s. In modern [[United States customary units|US customary units]] it is defined as {{frac|16|1|2}} [[Foot (unit)#United States survey foot|US survey feet]], equal to exactly {{frac|1|320}} of a [[Mile#U.S. survey mile|surveyor's mile]], or one-fourth of a [[surveyor's chain]], and is approximately 5.0292 metres. The rod is useful as a unit of length because whole number multiples of it can form one [[acre]] of square measure. The 'perfect acre'<ref name=\"Connections0\"/> is a rectangular area of 43,560 square feet, bounded by sides 660 feet (a [[furlong]]) long and 66 feet wide (220 yards and 22 yards) or, equivalently, 40 rods and 4 rods. An acre is therefore 160 square rods.\n\nThe name ''perch'' derives from the [[Ancient Roman units of measurement|Ancient Roman unit]], the ''pertica''.\nThe measure also has a relationship to the military [[pike (weapon)|pike]] of about the same size. Both measures<ref name=\"Connections\"/> date from the sixteenth century,<ref name=\"Connections2\"/> when the pike was still utilized in national armies. The tool has largely been supplanted by electronic tools such as surveyor lasers ([[Lidar]]) and optical target devices for surveying lands. Surveyors rods and chains are still used in rough terrains with heavy overgrowth where laser or other optical measurements are difficult or impossible. In dialectal English the term ''lug'' has also been used.<ref name=bonten/><ref name=\"dict-lug\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:A Meat Stall with the Holy Family Giving Alms - Placard.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The sign <!-- in the upper right corner --> included in [[Pieter Aertsen]]'s painting ''[[A Meat Stall with the Holy Family Giving Alms]]'' reads in [[Flemish]]: \"behind here are 154 rods of land for sale immediately, either by the rod according to your convenience or all at once\".]]\nIn England, the perch was officially discouraged in favour of the rod as early as the 15th century;<ref>[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]], English measure{{Better source|reason=More detail needed - There are many editions of Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica and each edition has multiple articles.|date=July 2013}}</ref> however, local customs maintained its use. In the 13th century perches were variously recorded in lengths of {{convert|18|ft|m|2}}, {{convert|20|ft|m|1}}, {{convert|22|ft|m|2}} and {{convert|24|ft|m|2}}; and even as late as 1820, a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] report notes lengths of {{convert|16+1/2|ft|m|2}}, {{convert|18|ft|m|2}}, {{convert|21|ft|m|1}}, {{convert|24|ft|m|2}}, and even {{convert|25|ft|m|2}}.<ref>United Kingdom. House of Commons Report (Second) of Commissioners to Consider the Subject of Weights and Measures, 13 July 1820. Parliamentary Papers 1820. (HC314) Pages 473\u2013512.</ref>  In [[Ireland]], a perch was standardized at {{convert|21|ft|m|1}}, making an Irish chain, [[furlong]] and mile proportionately longer by 27.27% than the \"standard\" English measure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/dictP.html|title=Units: P|author=|date=|website=www.unc.edu}}</ref>\n\nUntil English King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] seized the lands of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in 1536,<ref name=\"Connections\">{{cite book|last=Burke|first=James|title=Connections: Alternative History of Technology|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8IjaYgEACAAJ|year=1978|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-333-29066-8|chapter=9|page=304}}</ref> land measures as we now know them were essentially unknown.<ref name=\"Connections\"/> Instead a narrative system of landmarks and lists was used. Henry wanted to raise even more funds for his wars than he'd seized directly from church property (he'd also assumed the debts of Monasteries<ref name=\"Connections\"/>), and as [[James Burke (science historian)|James Burke]] writes and quotes in the book ''[[Connections (book)|Connections]]'': the English monk [[Richard Benese]] \"produced a book on how to survey land using the simple tools of the time, a rod with cord carrying knots at certain intervals, waxed and resined against wet weather.\" Benese poetically described the measure of an acre in terms of a perch:<ref name=\"Connections2\">''Connections'', pbk. p.263</ref>\n{{Cquote|an acre bothe of woodlande, also of fyldlande [heath] is always forty perches in length, and four perches in breadth, though an acre of woodlande be more in quantitie [value, was more valued commercially] than an acre of fyldelande|Richard Benese per James Burke in ''Connections'', pp 263}}\nThe practice of using surveyor's chains, and perch-length rods made into a detachable stiff chain, came about a century later when iron was a more plentiful and common material. A [[chain (unit)|chain]] is a larger [[Units of measurement|unit]] of [[length]] measuring {{convert|66|ft|4|lk=on}}, or 22 [[yard (unit of length)|yards]], or 100 [[Link (unit)|links]],<ref>The Cassell English Dictionary, London 1990, p. 214, {{ISBN|0-304-34003-0}}</ref> or 4 rods (20.1168 [[metre]]s). There are 10 chains or 40 rods in a [[furlong]] (eighth-mile), and so 80 chains or 320 rods in one [[statute mile]] (1760 yards, 1609.344 m, 1.609344 [[kilometre|km]]); the definition of which was set  by Royal surveyor (called the 'sworn viewer'<ref name=\"Connections3\">\"Connections\", pbk. pp265</ref>) [[John Ogilby]] only after the [[Great Fire of London]] (1666).\n\nAn [[acre]] is defined as the area of 10 square chains (that is, an area of one chain by one furlong), and derives from the shapes of new-tech plows<ref name=\"Connections0\">Connections, pbk. pp63</ref> and the desire to quickly survey seized church lands into a quantity of squares for quick sales<ref name=\"Connections2\"/> by Henry VIII's agents; buyers simply wanted to know what they were buying whereas Henry was raising cash for wars against Scotland and France.<ref name=\"Connections2\"/> Consequently, the surveyor's chain and surveyor rods or poles (the perch) have been used for several centuries in Britain and in many other countries influenced by British practices such as North America and Australia. By the time of the industrial revolution and the quickening of land sales, canal and railway surveys, et al. Surveyor rods such as used by [[George Washington]] were generally made of dimensionally stable metal&mdash;semi-flexible drawn wrought iron linkable bar stock (not steel), such that the four folded elements of a chain were easily transportable through brush and branches when carried by a single man of a surveyor's crew. With a direct ratio to the length of a surveyor's chain and the sides of both an acre and a square (mile), they were common tools used by surveyors, if only to lay out a known plottable baseline in rough terrain thereafter serving as the reference line for instrumental ([[theodolite]]) [[triangulation]]s.\n\nThe rod as a [[Surveying|survey]] measure was standardized by [[Edmund Gunter]] in England in 1607 as one-fourth of a [[chain (unit)|chain]] (of {{convert|66|ft|m|2}}), or {{convert|16+1/2|ft|m|2}} long.\n\n===In ancient cultures===\nThe '''perch''' as a [[Ancient Roman units of measurement|lineal measure in Rome]] (also ''decempeda'') was {{convert|10|ft|m|2}}, and in [[France]] varied from 10 feet (''perche romanie'') to 22 feet (''perche d'arpent''\u2014apparently {{frac|1|10}} of \"the range of an arrow\"\u2014about 220 feet). To confuse matters further, by ancient Roman definition, an arpent equalled 120 Roman feet. The related unit of square measure was the ''scrupulum'' or ''decempeda quadrata'', equivalent to about {{convert|8.76|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=smith/>\n\n===In continental Europe===\n[[Image:M\u00fcnster, Historisches Rathaus, Preussische halbe Ruthe -- 2017 -- 9783 (crop).jpg|thumb|300px|right|A standard at the City Hall in [[M\u00fcnster]], [[Germany]] from 1816; the bar shown is one \"Prussian Half Rod\" (1.883&nbsp;m) long.]]\nUnits comparable to the perch, pole or rod were used in many European countries, with names that include {{lang-fr|perche}} and ''canne'', {{lang-de|Ruthe}}, {{lang-it|canna}} and ''pertica'', {{lang-pl|pr\u0119t}} and {{lang-es|canna}}. They were subdivided in many different ways, and were of many different lengths.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Rods and similar units in continental Europe{{dubious|date=April 2012}}\n|-\n! width=240 |Place\n! width=130 |Local name\n! width=130 |Local equivalent\n! width=120 |Metric equivalent (metres)\n|-\n| [[Aachen]]\n| Feldme\u00dfruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.512<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Amsterdam]]\n| Roede\n| align=\"right\" | 13 Voet\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.681<ref name=\"DeGelder1824\">{{cite book\n|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XYVbAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|title = Allereerste Gronden der Cijferkunst\n|author = Jacob de Gelder\n|location = \u2019s-Gravenhage (The Hague) and Amsterdam\n|language = Dutch\n|year = 1824\n|pages = 163\u2013176\n|publisher = de Gebroeders van Cleef\n|trans-title=Introduction to arithmetic\n|accessdate = 2017-06-13}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Aubenas]], [[Ard\u00e8che]]\n| canne\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''pans''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.985<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Grand Duchy of Baden|Baden, Grand Duchy of]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.0<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Canton of Basel|Basel, Canton of]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.864<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Canton of Bern|Bern, Canton of]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.932<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Barcelona]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmos''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.581<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Braunschweig]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.565<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Bremen]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 8 Ellen or 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.626<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Brussels]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 20 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.654<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Cagliari]], [[Sardinia]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 10 ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.322<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Calenberg|Calenberg Land]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.677<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Kassel|Cassel]], [[Hessen]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 14 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.026<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Denmark]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.138<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Canton of Geneva|Geneva, Canton of]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 8 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.598<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Hamburg]]\n| Geestruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.583<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Hamburg\n| Marschruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 14 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.010<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Kingdom of Hannover|Hannover]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.671<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[France]]\n| Perche\n| align=\"right\" | 3 ''[[toise]]s''\n| \talign=\"center\"|5.847<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| France\n| Perche (for woodland)\n| align=\"right\" | {{frac|3|2|3}} ''toises''\n| \talign=\"center\"|7.145<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Genoa]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 10 ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.5<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Jever]], [[Duchy of Oldenburg|Oldenburg]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 20 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.377<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Mallorca]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmos''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.714<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Malta]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.08<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Mecklenburg]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.655<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Menorca]], but not [[Mah\u00f3n]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" |\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.599<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Menorca, city of Mahon\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmos''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.714<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Messina]], [[Sicily]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.113<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Montauban]], [[Tarn-et-Garonne]]\n| canne\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''pans''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.783<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Morocco]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmos''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.714<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Naples]]\n| canna (for cloth)\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmi''\n| align=\"center\"|\n|-\n| [[Kingdom of Naples|Naples, Kingdom of]]: [[Apulia]], [[Calabria]], [[Eboli]], [[Foggia]], [[Lucera]]\n| percha\n| align=\"right\" | 7 [[Palm (unit)|''palmi'']]\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.838<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Naples, Kingdom of: [[Capua]]\n| percha\n| align=\"right\" | {{frac|7|1|5}} ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.892<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Naples, Kingdom of: Fiano, Naples\n| percha\n| align=\"right\" | {{frac|7|1|2}} ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.014<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Naples, Kingdom of: [[Caggiano]], [[Cava de' Tirreni|Cava]], [[Nocera Superiore|Nocera]], Rocce, [[Salerno]]\n| percha\n| align=\"right\" | {{frac|7|2|3}} palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.971<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Nuremberg]], Bavaria\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.861<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Oldenburg]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 20 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|5.927<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Palermo]], Sicily\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''palmi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.942<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Parma]]\n| Pertica\n| align=\"right\" | 6 [[braccio|''bracci'']]\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.25<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Poland]]\n| Pr\u0119t\n| align=\"right\" | {{frac|7|1|2}} ''\u0142okci'' or 10 ''pr\u0119cik\u00f3w''\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.320<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Prussia]], [[Rhine Province|Rheinland]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 12 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.766<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Rijnland]]\n| Roede\n| align=\"right\" | 12 Voet\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.767<ref name=\"DeGelder1824\"/>\n|-\n| [[Rome]]\n| canna (for cloth)\n| align=\"right\" |\n| \talign=\"center\"|2<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| Rome\n| canna (for building)\n| align=\"right\" |\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.234<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Zaragoza|Saragoza]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" |\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.043<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Kingdom of Saxony|Saxony]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Leipziger Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.512<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Sweden]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.748<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Tortosa]]\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" |\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.7<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Tuscany, Grand-Duchy of]] ([[Florence]], [[Pisa]])\n| canna\n| align=\"right\" | 5 bracci\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.918<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Uz\u00e8s]], [[Gard]]\n| canne\n| align=\"right\" | 8 ''pans''\n| \talign=\"center\"|1.98<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Vaud|Waadt, Canton of]]\n| Ruthe or ''toise courante''\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|3<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n| Reichsruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.865<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| W\u00fcrttemberg\n| old Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 16 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|4.583<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Republic of Venice|Venice, Republic of]]\n| Pertica\n| align=\"right\" | 6 ''piedi''\n| \talign=\"center\"|2.084<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n| [[Canton of Zurich|Z\u00fcrich, Canton of]]\n| Ruthe\n| align=\"right\" | 10 Fu\u00df\n| \talign=\"center\"|3.009<sup>N</sup>\n|-\n|}\nBased on data from the following:\n*<sup>N</sup> - Niemann ([[Quedlinburg]] and [[Leipzig]] - 1830).<ref name=kruger/>\n\n===In Britain===\nIn England, the rod or perch was first defined in law by the [[Composition of Yards and Perches]], one of the [[statutes of uncertain date]] from the late 13th to early 14th centuries: ''tres pedes faciunt ulnam, quinque ulne & dimidia faciunt perticam'' (three feet make a yard, five and a half yards make a perch).<ref>{{cite book|title=The statutes at large. |location = London | publisher= Charles Eyre and Andrew Strahan|year= 1794 |url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cKQ3AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA400|page=200}}</ref>\n\nThe length of the ''[[Chain (unit)|chain]]'' was standardized in 1620 by [[Edmund Gunter]] at exactly four rods.<ref name=Taylor/><ref name=Russell/> Fields were measured in ''[[acres]]'', which were one [[chain (length)|chain]] (four rods) by one [[furlong]] (in the United Kingdom, ten chains).<ref name=\"dict-acre\"/>\n\nBars of metal one rod long were used as standards of length when [[surveying]] land. The rod was still in use as a common unit of measurement in the mid-19th century, when [[Henry David Thoreau]] used it frequently when describing distances in his work, ''[[Walden]]''.<ref name=\"Thoreau1899\"/>\n\n[[Image:Holyrood Palace and Abbey from above.jpg|right|thumb|Holyrood, Edinburgh]]\n\nIn traditional [[Scottish units]], a ''Scottish rood'' (''ruid'' in [[Scots language|Lowland Scots]], ''r\u00f2d'' in [[Scottish Gaelic]]), also ''[[fall (Scots)|fall]]'' measures 222 inches.<ref>\"fall, faw\", ''[[Dictionary of the Scottish Language]] \u2013 [[Dictionary of the Older Scottish Tongue]]'' [http://www.dsl.ac.uk/ online edition].</ref>\n\n==Modern use==\nThe rod was phased out as a legal unit of measurement in the United Kingdom as part of a ten-year metrication process that began on 24 May 1965.<ref name=dti/>\n\nIn the US, the rod, along with the chain, furlong, and statute mile (as well as the survey inch and survey foot) are based on the pre-1959 values for [[United States customary units]] of linear measurement. The [[Mendenhall Order]] of 1893 defined the yard as exactly {{frac|3600|3937}} metres, with all other units of linear measurement, including the rod, based on the yard. In 1959, an international agreement (the [[International yard and pound]] agreement), defined the yard as the fundamental unit of length in the Imperial/USCU system, defined as exactly 0.9144 metres. However, the above-noted units, when used in surveying, may retain their pre-1959 values, depending on the legislation in each state.<ref>Michael L. Dennis, ''[https://geodesy.noaa.gov/library/pdfs/NOAA_SP_NOS_NGS_0013_v01_2018-03-06.pdf The State Plane Coordinate System: History, Policy, and Future Directions]'' (n.p.: National Geodetic Survey, March 6, 2018), Appendix C.</ref> {{As of|2020}} there are plans by [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey]] and [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] to replace the definition for the above mentioned units by the International 1959 defintion of the feet, being exactly 0.3048 metres. <ref>{{cite web |title=NGS and NIST to Retire U.S. Survey Foot after 2022 |url=https://www.ngs.noaa.gov/web/news/us-survey-foot.shtml |publisher=National Geodetic Survey |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Survey Foot: Revised Unit Conversion Factors |url=https://www.nist.gov/pml/us-surveyfoot/revised-unit-conversion-factors |publisher=NIST |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite no longer being in widespread use, the rod is still employed in certain specialized fields. In recreational [[canoe]]ing, maps measure [[portage]]s (overland paths where canoes must be carried) in rods; typical canoes are approximately one rod long.<ref name=\"canoe1\"/> The term is also in widespread use in the acquisition of [[pipeline transport|pipeline]] [[easement]]s, as the offers for an easement are often expressed on a \"price per rod\".<ref>[http://www.pipelineattorney.com/learning-resources/pipeline-terminology.html Attorney Discussion on Price per Rod]. Retrieved 24 Oct 2012.</ref>\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], the sizes of [[allotment (gardening)|allotment]] [[garden]]s continue to be measured in square poles in some areas, sometimes being referred to simply as ''poles'' rather than ''square poles''.<ref name=allot/>\n\nIn [[Vermont]], the default [[right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]] width of state and town highways and trails is three rods (49.5 feet or 15.0876 m).<ref name=vermont/> Rods can also be found on the older legal descriptions of tracts of land in the [[United States]], following the \"[[metes and bounds]]\" method of land survey;<ref name=shelton/> as shown in this actual legal description of rural real estate: {{quote|LEGAL DESCRIPTION: Commencing 45 rods East and 44 rods North of Southwest corner of Southwest 1/4 of Southwest 1/4; thence North 36 rods; thence East 35 rods; thence South 36 rods; thence West 35 rods to the place of beginning, Manistique Township, Schoolcraft County, Michigan.<ref name=\"property\"/>}}\n\n=={{anchor|Area}}<!-- [[Square perch]] and [[Rod (area)]] redirect here-->Area and volume==\nThe terms ''pole'', ''perch'', ''rod'' and ''rood'' have been used as units of area, and ''perch'' is also used as a unit of volume. As a unit of [[area]], a ''square perch'' (the perch being standardized to equal {{frac|16|1|2}} feet, or {{frac|5|1|2}} yards) is equal to a '''square rod''', {{convert|30+1/4|sqyd|m2|2|abbr=off|lk=out}} or {{frac|160}} acre.  There are 40 square perches to a [[Rood (measurement)|rood]] (for example a rectangular area of 40 rods times one rod), and 160 square perches to an [[acre]] (for example a rectangular area of 40 rods times 4 rods). This unit is usually referred to as a ''perch'' or ''pole'' even though ''square perch'' and ''square pole'' were the more precise terms. Confusingly, ''rod'' was also sometimes used as a unit of area to refer to a rood.\n\nHowever, in the traditional French-based system in some countries, 1 square ''perche'' is 42.21 square metres.\n\nAs of August 2013 perches and roods are used as government survey units in [[Jamaica]]. They appear on most property title documents. The perch is also in extensive use in [[Sri Lanka]], being favored even over the rood and acre in real estate listings there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srilankapropertymarket.com/LFS_page1.html|title=srilankapropertymarket.com - srilankapropertymarket Resources and Information.|author=|date=|website=www.srilankapropertymarket.com}}</ref> Perches were informally used as a measure in [[Queensland]] [[real estate]] until the early 21st century, mostly for historical gazetted properties in older suburbs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebuzz.beesnees.com.au/tag/dutton-park-real-estate-agent/|title=Dutton Park real estate agent Archives - Bees Nees|author=|date=|website=Bees Nees}}</ref>\n\n===Volume===\n\nA traditional unit of volume for stone and other masonry. A perch of masonry is the volume of a stone wall one perch ({{convert|16+1/2|ft|m|2|disp=or}}) long, {{convert|18|in|cm|1}} high, and {{convert|12|in|cm|1}} thick. This is equivalent to exactly {{convert|24+3/4|cuft|cuyd m3 l|abbr=off}}.\n\nThere are two different measurements for a perch depending on the type of masonry that is being built:\n\n#A dressed stone work is measured by the {{frac|24|3|4}}-cubic foot perch ({{convert|16+1/2|ft|m|2|disp=or}}) long, {{convert|18|in|cm|1}} high, and {{convert|12|in|cm|1}} thick. This is equivalent to exactly {{convert|24+3/4|cuft|cuyd m3|6|abbr=off}}.\n#a brick work or rubble wall made of broken stone of irregular size, shape and texture, made of undressed stone, is measured by the ({{convert|16+1/2|ft|m|2|disp=or}}) long, {{convert|12|in|cm|1}} high, and {{convert|12|in|cm|1}} thick. This is equivalent to exactly {{convert|16+1/2|cuft|cuyd m3|6|abbr=off}}.<ref>''see'' McClurg/Shoemaker.''The Building Estimator's Reference Handbook.''  17th Ed. Chicago: Frank R. Walker Company, 1970, p. 1644.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chain (unit)]]\n* [[Furlong]]\n* [[Imperial units]]\n* [[English units]]\n* [[United States customary units]]\n* [[Anthropic units]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1=2|refs=\n\n<ref name=allot>{{cite web |url=http://www.watford.gov.uk/ccm/navigation/environment-and-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/allotments/ |title=Allotments |publisher=[[Watford Borough Council]] |accessdate=2009-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814005118/http://www.watford.gov.uk/ccm/navigation/environment-and-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/allotments/ |archivedate=2009-08-14 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bonten>{{cite web | url = http://home.kpn.nl/jhm.bonten/tables/anglosaxon/napolangsax.html#linsur | title = Anglo-Saxon and Biblical to Metrics Conversions | last = Bonten | first = JHM | date = 2007-01-19 | at = Surveyor + Chain + British-Nautical | accessdate = 2010-11-01 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"canoe1\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.outdoorplaces.com/Features/Paddle/pickcanoe/newcanoe7.htm#rod\n| title = Canoe Glossary and Clickable Canoe\n| work = OutdoorPlaces.com\n| publisher = Michael Thiessen\n| accessdate = 2010-11-01\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"dict-acre\">{{cite encyclopedia\n| url = http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/dictA.html\n| title = acre (ac or A)\n| encyclopedia = How Many? A Dictionary of Units of Measurement\n| last = Rowlett\n| first = Russ\n| publisher = University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill\n| date = 2008-12-03\n| accessdate = 2010-11-01\n}}{{dead link|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"dict-lug\">{{cite encyclopedia\n| url = http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/dictL.html\n| title = lug <nowiki>[1]</nowiki>\n| encyclopedia = How Many? A Dictionary of Units of Measurement\n| last = Rowlett\n| first = Russ\n| 