le4          = In Its Own Little Way\n| writer4         = {{hlist|B. West|D. West}}\n| length4         = 2:19\n| title5          = Take Me as I Am (Or Let Me Go)\n| writer5         = Bryant\n| length5         = 2:51\n| title6          = No One Will Ever Know\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Forre|Rose}}\n| length6         = 2:44\n| title7          = Didn't I\n| writer7         = D. West\n| length7         = 2:42\n| title8          = Mama, Kiss the Hurt Away\n| writer8         = {{hlist|B. West|D. West}}\n| length8         = 2:50\n| title9          = Touch Me\n| writer9         = Nelson\n| length9         = 2:29\n| title10          = Mama, You'd Have Been Proud of Me\n| writer10         = Cochran\n| length10         = 2:47\n| title11          = I Dreamed of an Old Affair\n| writer11         = {{hlist|Davis|Dodd|Mitchell}}\n| length11         = 2:39\n| title12          = All the World Is Lonely Now\n| writer12         = {{hlist|Acuff|Foree}}\n| length12         = 2:22\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nAll credits are adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Here Comes My Baby''.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n'''Musical personnel'''\n* [[Willie Ackerman]] \u2013 [[drums]]\n* [[Harold Bradley]] \u2013 [[guitar]]\n* [[Kenneth Buttrey]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Floyd Cramer]] \u2013 [[piano]]\n* [[Ray Edenton]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Buddy Harman]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Anita Kerr|The Anita Kerr Sings]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Grady Martin]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] \u2013 [[bass (instrument)|bass]]\n* [[Jerry Reed]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Hargus \"Pig\" Robbins]] \u2013 piano\n* Velma Smith \u2013 guitar\n* [[Henry Strzelecki]] \u2013 bass\n* Bill West \u2013 [[steel guitar]]\n* Dottie West \u2013 lead vocals\n\n'''Technical personnel'''\n* Chet Atkins \u2013 producer\n* Anita Kerr \u2013 arrangement\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1965)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCountry|12|artist=Dottie West|rowheader=true|date=20200121|accessdate=April 26, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Format\n!scope=\"col\"| Label\n!scope=\"col\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n| July 1965\n| Vinyl\n| [[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]\n| <ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n|-\n| 2010\n| Music download\n| [[LMG, LLC|LMG]]\n| <ref name=\"Apple\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dottie West}}\n[[Category:1965 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Chet Atkins]]\n[[Category:Country albums by American artists]]\n[[Category:Dottie West albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Here Comes My Baby\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Dottie West]]\n| cover      = Dottie West-Here Comes the Album.jpg\n| released   = {{start date|1965|06}}\n| recorded   = 1963\u20131965\n| studio     = RCA Victor Studio\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Country music|Country]]|[[Nashville Sound]]<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web |title=''Here Comes My Baby'' -- Dottie West -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/here-comes-my-baby-mw0000857979 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]\n| producer   = [[Chet Atkins]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Dottie West Sings]]\n| next_year  = 1965\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Here Comes My Baby\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Here Comes My Baby (Dottie West song)|Here Comes My Baby]]\n | single1date = June 1964\n | single2     = Didn't I\n | single2date = November 1964\n }}\n}}\n'''''Here Comes My Baby''''' is a studio album by American [[country music]] artist [[Dottie West]]. It was released in June 1965 on [[RCA Records|RCA Victor Records]] and was produced by [[Chet Atkins]]. It was West's debut studio album as a recording artist and was issued following the success of the [[Here Comes My Baby (Dottie West song)|title track]] in 1964. The latter song won a [[Grammy Award]] in early 1965 which prompted the issue of the album. ''Here Comes My Baby'' would start a series of studio recordings West would release for RCA.\n\n==Background and content==\n''Here Comes My Baby'' was recorded in several studio sessions between 1963 and 1965. They were held at the RCA Victor Studio located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=West |first1=Dottie |title=''Here Comes My Baby'' (Liner Notes -- Vinyl insert) |journal=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]] |date=June 1965}}</ref> [[Chet Atkins]] served as the album's producer and would remain in collaboration with West throughout the 1960s. Atkins had recently signed her to RCA following [[Jim Reeves]]' recommendation.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web |last1=Ankeny |first1=Jason |title=Dottie West: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/dottie-west-mn0000190632/biography |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> Reeves had recorded a song by West that became a hit in 1963. Atkins was impressed by West's own singing, signing her to the roster and began recording her voice in February 1963. In those first sessions, West recorded a cover of [[Willie Nelson]]'s \"[[Touch Me (Willie Nelson song)|Touch Me]]\", which appears on \"side two\" of the record. Another album track from the early sessions is the song \"Didn't I\". The original version went unreleased until it was re-recorded several months later.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n''Here Comes My Baby'' consisted of 12 tracks. Five of the album's tracks were written or co-written by West. Her husband, Bill West, co-wrote tracks with her and also played steel guitar on the recording sessions.<ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web |title=Dottie West -- ''Here Comes My Baby'' (1965, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Dottie-West-Here-Comes-My-Baby/release/2211128 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> The album also included cover versions of songs previously recorded by other artists. Among these songs is another [[Willie Nelson]] tune entitled \"[[Night Life (Willie Nelson song)|Night Life]]\". The song would later be cut by [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]] before West's version appeared as the album's second track on \"side one\" of the LP. The sixth track on side A was a cover of [[Hank Williams]]' \"[[No One Will Ever Know]]\". Also included is a song written by [[Roy Acuff]] called \"All the World Is Lonely Now\".<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n==Release and reception==\nAlthough West had been signed to the RCA Victor label since 1963, the label did not release ''Here Comes My Baby'' until 1965. West's first single to become a hit was a duet with Jim Reeves. However, the song did not appear on this album.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The first single released in preparation for the album was \"Touch Me\" in April 1963. The song did not chart any major recording publications and the album was delayed.<ref name=\"Billboard Singles\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}<!--|accessdate=2011-04-01--></ref> The album's title track was the song that prompted the LP's release.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> Issued as a single in June 1964,<ref name=\"Billboard Singles\"/> the song spent 15 weeks on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart before peaking at number ten in September.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Here Comes My Baby\" [single] chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dottie-west/chart-history/CSI/song/839106 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> The title track became West's first major hit as a solo artist and won her the first [[Grammy Award]] to be given to a female country recording artist in 1965.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Following its success, a second single was released to prepare for the album. The single, \"Didn't I\" was released in November 1964 and was later featured on the album.<ref name=\"Billboard Singles\"/> Spending eight weeks charting, the single reached number 32 on the ''Billboard'' country chart, becoming a minor hit.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Didn't I\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dottie-west/chart-history/CSI/song/837334 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Here Comes My Baby'' was eventually released in June 1965 on the RCA Victor label, becoming her debut LP as a recording artist.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> The album was issued first as a [[gramophone record|vinyl LP]] with six songs included on side one and side two.<ref name=\"Discogs\"/> It was later released in 2016 as a [[compact disc]]. Released as a compilation, combined both ''Here Comes My Baby'' and her second album together in one track listing.<ref>{{cite web |title=WEST, DOTTIE -- ''Here Comes My Baby/Dottie West Sings'' |url=https://www.amazon.com/Here-Comes-Baby-Dottie-Sings/dp/B01J2MF4H0/ref=tmm_acd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1587786852&sr=8-1 |website=[[Amazon (website)|Amazon]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> In 2010, the album was released to digital retailers and the track listing remained the same.<ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite web |title=''Here Comes My Baby'' by Dottie West on Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/tr/album/here-comes-my-baby/571729457 |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> In its initial release, ''Here Comes My Baby'' peaked at number 12 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart in July 1965, spending 12 weeks on the list overall.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Here Comes My Baby'' [LP] chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dottie-west/chart-history/CLP/song/831726 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=25 April 2020}}</ref> ''Here Comes My Baby'' received a positive response upon its initial release in 1965. Writers for ''Billboard'' gave it a positive reception in their June 1965 issue. \"This is a beautifully produced package, with the enchantress' voice showcased tasteful instrumental and choral arrangements,\" staff writers commented.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Album Reviews |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 12, 1965 |volume=77 |issue=24 |page=28}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n===Original vinyl version===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n| title1          = [[Here Comes My Baby (Dottie West song)|Here Comes My Baby]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|Bill West|Dottie West}}\n| length1         = 2:31\n| title2          = [[Night Life (Willie Nelson song)|Night Life]]\n| writer2         = {{hlist|Walt Breeland|Paul Buskirk|[[Willie Nelson]]}}\n| length2         = 2:18\n| title3          = That's Where Our Love Must Be\n| writer3         = D. West\n| length3         = 2:38\n| title4          = In Its Own Little Way\n| writer4         = {{hlist|B. West|D. West}}\n| length4         = 2:19\n| title5          = Take Me as I Am (Or Let Me Go)\n| writer5         = [[Felice and Boudleaux Bryant|Boudleaux Bryant]]\n| length5         = 2:51\n| title6          = [[No One Will Ever Know]]\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Mel Forre|[[Fred Rose (songwriter)|Fred Rose]]}}\n| length6         = 2:44\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n| title1          = Didn't I\n| writer1         = D. West\n| length1         = 2:42\n| title2          = Mama, Kiss the Hurt Away\n| writer2         = {{hlist|B. West|D. West}}\n| length2         = 2:50\n| title3          = [[Touch Me (Willie Nelson song)|Touch Me]]\n| writer3         = Nelson\n| length3         = 2:29\n| title4          = Mama, You'd Have Been Proud of Me\n| writer4         = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| length4         = 2:47\n| title5          = I Dreamed of an Old Affair\n| writer5        